ntal illness, which included liberating patients from the chains and restraints that were commonly used in asylums at the time. Pinel transformed these institutions into more humane hospitals, emphasizing care and treatment over confinement and punishment. Additionally, he made important advancements in the classification of mental disorders, categorizing them into four distinct groups. His work laid the foundation for modern psychiatry and marked a turning point in the understanding and treatment of mental illness.", "KRAEPELIN:Kraepelin was a prominent German psychiatrist who made significant contributions to the field of mental health through his classification of mental illnesses. He advanced the understanding of psychiatric disorders by focusing on clinical observations and etiology, which laid the groundwork for modern psychiatric diagnoses. Kraepelin is particularly known for his classification of non-organic mental disorders into distinct categories, including schizophrenia, manic-depressive psychosis (now known as bipolar disorder), and paranoia. His work has had a lasting influence on the field of psychiatry, shaping the way mental illnesses are diagnosed and treated today.", "GRIESINGER:Griesinger was a psychiatrist who proposed that mental illnesses are caused by brain disorders, marking the beginning of modern psychiatry"], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-v3"}}}